Sure! I can help you create a Vue.js component called "Step" that represents a step with an unchecked square, message content, and a loader animation. The component will have a boolean property called "done" that determines whether the step is completed or not.

Here's an example implementation of the "Step" component:

```vue
<template>
  <div class="step">
    <div class="checkbox" :class="{ checked: done }"></div>
    <div class="content">{{ message }}</div>
    <div class="loader" v-if="!done"></div>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  props: {
    done: {
      type: Boolean,
      required: true
    },
    message: {
      type: String,
      required: true
    }
  }
};
</script>

<style>
.step {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.checkbox {
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  margin-right: 10px;
}

.checkbox.checked {
  background-color: #007bff;
}

.content {
  flex: 1;
}

.loader {
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  border: 3px solid #007bff;
  border-top-color: transparent;
  animation: spin 1s linear infinite;
}

@keyframes spin {
  0% {
    transform: rotate(0deg);
  }
  100% {
    transform: rotate(360deg);
  }
}
</style>
```

In this example, the component receives two props: "done" and "message". The "done" prop determines the state of the step (whether it is completed or not), and the "message" prop contains the content of the step.

The component template consists of a `<div>` element with three child elements. The first child element represents the square checkbox, and its appearance is controlled using the "done" prop. If "done" is true, the "checked" class is applied to the checkbox, making it appear checked. The second child element displays the message content. The third child element is a loader animation, which is shown when the step is not done.

The component's style defines the appearance of the elements, including the checkbox, content, and loader animation.

You can use this "Step" component in your Vue.js application to represent each step in your socket.io task. You would need to pass the "done" and "message" values as props when using the component.

Here's an example usage of the "Step" component:

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <Step v-for="step in steps" :key="step.id" :done="step.done" :message="step.message" />
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import Step from '@/components/Step.vue';

export default {
  components: {
    Step
  },
  data() {
    return {
      steps: [
        { id: 1, done: false, message: 'Step 1 in progress' },
        { id: 2, done: true, message: 'Step 2 completed' },
        { id: 3, done: false, message: 'Step 3 in progress' }
      ]
    };
  }
};
</script>
```

In this example, the parent component iterates over an array of "steps" and renders the "Step" component for each step. The "done" and "message" values for each step are passed as props to the "Step" component.

