Here's a step-by-step guide to getting started:

1. Install the Socket.IO Client C++ library:
   - Clone the Socket.IO Client C++ repository from GitHub: `git clone https://github.com/socketio/socket.io-client-cpp.git`
   - Build and install the library by following the instructions provided in the repository's README file.

2. Include the necessary headers in your C++ code:
   ```cpp
   #include <iostream>
   #include <string>
   #include <socket.io-client-cpp/src/sio_client.h>
   ```

3. Set up a connection to the Socket.IO server:
   ```cpp
   sio::client client;
   client.connect("http://your-socket-io-server-url");
   ```

4. Define event handlers to handle incoming events from the server:
   ```cpp
   void onConnected()
   {
       std::cout << "Connected to the server" << std::endl;
   }

   void onCustomEvent(const std::string& eventName, const sio::message::list& args, bool isAck, sio::message::list& ackResponse)
   {
       std::cout << "Received custom event: " << eventName << std::endl;
       // Handle the event data as needed
   }
   ```

5. Register the event handlers:
   ```cpp
   client.set_open_listener([&]() {
       onConnected();
   });

   client.socket()->on("customEvent", [&](const sio::event& event) {
       onCustomEvent(event.get_name(), event.get_message()->get_vector(), event.has_ack(), event.get_ack_response());
   });
   ```

6. Emit signals to the server:
   ```cpp
   std::string message = "Hello, server!";
   client.socket()->emit("myEvent", sio::string_message::create(message));
   ```

7. Run the event loop:
   ```cpp
   client.sync_close();
   ```

This is a basic example to get you started. You can expand upon it to handle more events and implement additional functionality as needed.

Remember to link against the Socket.IO Client C++ library during the compilation process. Refer to the library's documentation for more advanced usage and options.

