It doesn't render the headers correctly (ie: # and ##)

The issue with your Markdown renderer lies in the configuration of the `markdown-it` library. By default, `markdown-it` treats the `#` and `##` characters as regular text instead of header indicators. To fix this, you need to enable the `heading` plugin of `markdown-it` and specify the appropriate options.

Here's the modified code with the necessary changes:

```javascript
// ...

import attrs from 'markdown-it-attrs';
import heading from 'markdown-it-heading';

// ...

const markdownIt = new MarkdownIt('commonmark', {
  // ...
}).use(emoji).use(attrs).use(heading);

// ...
```

By adding `heading` to the list of plugins, you enable support for rendering headers correctly. Make sure you have the `markdown-it-heading` package installed in your project.

With this change, the `#` and `##` characters in your Markdown text will be recognized as header indicators, and the renderer will output the corresponding HTML tags (`h1` and `h2`).

To install and use the `markdown-it-anchor` plugin, you can follow these steps:

1. Install the `markdown-it-anchor` package using npm or yarn:
```shell
npm install markdown-it-anchor
```

2. Import the `markdown-it-anchor` package in your code:
```javascript
import anchor from 'markdown-it-anchor';
```

3. Register the `markdown-it-anchor` plugin with `markdown-it`:
```javascript
const markdownIt = new MarkdownIt('commonmark', {
  // ...
}).use(emoji).use(attrs).use(heading).use(anchor);
```

4. Customize the options for `markdown-it-anchor` if needed. For example, you can specify the slugify function to control how the anchor links are generated:
```javascript
const markdownIt = new MarkdownIt('commonmark', {
  // ...
}).use(emoji).use(attrs).use(heading).use(anchor, {
  slugify: (s) => encodeURIComponent(String(s).trim().toLowerCase())
