If you're using Socket.IO with Python, you can use the power of event-driven programming to handle long-running tasks and allow communication between different endpoints. Here's an approach you can take:

1. Set up your Socket.IO server:
   ```python
   from flask import Flask
   from flask_socketio import SocketIO, emit

   app = Flask(__name__)
   socketio = SocketIO(app)

   # Your long-running program
   def long_running_program():
       while True:
           # Your code here
           socketio.emit('program_status', {'status': 'running'}, namespace='/program')

   # Define the endpoint to start the program
   @app.route('/start_program')
   def start_program():
       # Start the long-running program in a separate thread
       program_thread = threading.Thread(target=long_running_program)
       program_thread.start()
       return 'Program started'

   if __name__ == '__main__':
       socketio.run(app)
   ```

2. Connect to the Socket.IO server from your UI:
   ```javascript
   <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/socket.io/2.3.1/socket.io.js"></script>
   <script>
   const socket = io.connect('http://localhost:5000/program');

   // Listen for program status updates
   socket.on('program_status', function(data) {
       console.log('Program status:', data.status);
   });

   // Call the stop endpoint
   function stopProgram() {
       fetch('/stop_program', { method: 'POST' })
           .then(response => response.text())
           .then(message => console.log(message))
           .catch(error => console.error(error));
   }
   </script>
   ```

3. Define the endpoint to stop the program:
   ```python
   # Define your stop program endpoint
   @app.route('/stop_program', methods=['POST'])
   def stop_program():
       # Implement the logic to stop the long-running program
       # You can use a flag or any mechanism to signal the program to stop
       return 'Program stopped'
   ```

With this setup, the long-running program emits the current status through Socket.IO events. The UI can connect to the Socket.IO server and listen for these events to get real-time updates on the program status. When you call the `/stop_program` endpoint from the UI, it will trigger the necessary logic to stop the long-running program gracefully.

Remember to install the necessary dependencies (`flask`, `flask-socketio`, and `eventlet` or `gevent`) using `pip` to run the Socket.IO server.

